    "!pip install requests pandas\n",
    "import requests\n",
    "import json\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "18b4f6a1-5b4d-44f4-b653-181be338488b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "url = \"https://api.bls.gov/publicAPI/v2/timeseries/data/\"\n",
    "\n",
    "headers = {'Content-type': 'application/json'}\n",
    "data = json.dumps({\n",
    "    \"seriesid\": [\"CUUR0000SA0\"],\n",
    "    \"startyear\": \"2014\",\n",
    "    \"endyear\": \"2024\"\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "response = requests.post(url, data=data, headers=headers)\n",
    "json_data = json.loads(response.text)\n",
    "\n",
    "cpi_data = []\n",
    "for series in json_data[\"Results\"][\"series\"]:\n",
    "    series_id = series[\"seriesID\"]\n",
    "    for item in series[\"data\"]:\n",
    "        cpi_data.append([series_id, item[\"year\"], item[\"period\"], item[\"value\"]])\n",
    "\n",
    "df = pd.DataFrame(cpi_data, columns=[\"Series ID\", \"Year\", \"Period\", \"CPI Value\"])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "adbab527-22e8-4a9b-ac53-e7776871ce46",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Consumer Price Index CPI\n",
    "\n",
    "It is a measure that examines the average change in prices paid by consumers for goods and services over time. The CPI is often used to track inflation, as it reflects how the cost of living fluctuates. A higher-than-expected CPI signals rising inflation, which can lead central banks to tighten monetary policy by increasing interest rates. This often results in a bearish market cycle, as higher borrowing costs reduce corporate earnings and investor confidence."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# The sharp rise in Consumer Price Index (CPI) from late 2021 to the end of 2023 was driven by several key factors:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Supply Chain Disruptions\n",
    "-The lingering effects of the COVID-19 pandemic caused global supply chain bottlenecks, leading to shortages in goods and materials.\n",
    "-Semiconductor shortages affected industries like automobiles and electronics, pushing prices higher.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Energy Price Surge\n",
    "-Gas and oil prices spiked due to geopolitical tensions, including the Russia-Ukraine conflict, which disrupted global energy markets.\n",
    "-Higher energy costs increased transportation and production expenses, which were passed on to consumers.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Strong Demand Post-Pandemic\n",
    "-As economies reopened, pent-up consumer demand surged, driving up prices for travel, entertainment, and goods.\n",
    "-Governments provided stimulus packages, increasing disposable income and fueling spending.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Wage Growth & Labor Market Tightness\n",
    "-Labor shortages in many sectors led to higher wages, which contributed to inflation as businesses raised prices to offset costs.\n",
    "-The service sector, including hospitality and retail, saw significant price increases due to labor constraints.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Food Price Inflation\n",
    "-Extreme weather events and supply chain disruptions affected food production, leading to higher costs for essentials like grains and dairy.\n",
    "-Fertilizer shortages and increased transportation costs further drove up food prices.\n",
    "\n",
    "6. Central Bank Policies & Interest Rates\n",
    "-Initially, central banks kept interest rates low, which encouraged borrowing and spending.\n",
    "-As inflation surged, rate hikes were introduced to slow down demand, but price increases remained persistent."
   ]
  },

    "Consumer Price Index (CPI) vs. Stock Market Performance, here are the key findings:\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall Trends\n",
    "CPI has shown a gradual increase over time, reflecting rising consumer prices due to inflation. Whereas, the S&P 500 index returns exhibited periods of volatility, with both significant rallies and temporary declines.\n",
    "\n",
    "Key Observations\n",
    "1. Last quarter of 2019: Decline in CPI and Returns may have been caused by:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Market correction after a strong start to the year.\n",
    "- Central Bank Policies cutting interest rates to support economic growth.\n",
    "- Trade tensions between US and China led to cautious investors.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Huge drop in Returns during 2020 yet CPI remained fairly stable.\n",
    "\n",
    "- In early 2020, markets experienced a sharp decline as lockdowns, travel restrictions, and economic uncertainty led to panic selling. Investors pulled out of equities, causing a massive drop in returns.\n",
    "- Central Banks responded by cutting interest rates which helped stabilize CPI.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Increase in Returns during the end of 2020.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Government intervention helped restore investor confidence.\n",
    "- Tech stocks surge - e-commerce, communication and collaboration software saw an increase in demand. \n",
    "- Vaccine announcement.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. CPI steadily increasing since 2021\n",
    "\n",
    "-Supply chain disruptions caused by COVID-19 led to bottlenecks and shortages in goods and materials.\n",
    "- Energy price surge thanks to geopolitical tensions with Russia and Ukraine.\n",
    "- Food price inflation caused by extreme weather."

    "Our analysis highlights that CPI does not have a direct correlation with stock returns, suggesting that inflation alone is not a reliable predictor of market performance. Expanding on this, sector-specific trends, lagged effects, and broader macroeconomic variables may play a more influential role. Additionally, central bank policies and investor sentiment often drive market movements more than inflation metrics do.
